<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-419-160  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 419 160.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  April 30 1990 n588 p44(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>A step ahead. (Desktop Engineering) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Gabay, Jon.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A personal experience in printer selection questions whether theJapanese have begun to overlook quality in their manufacturing.andO;Ten years ago an Epson MX 100 contained many plastic parts, butthe machine is still operating today.andP;  A recently purchasedPanasonic 1180 lacks an intuitive interface, is difficult to use,and shreds ribbons into inked lint balls before the ink runs out.andO;The Japanese manufacturing infrastructure is still more efficientthan America's but many fresh ideas still flow from the US.andP;  Acase in point: the Japanese manufacture the basic print engine forHewlett-Packard's laser printer, but HP put it together with goodcontrol electronics, language interfaces and high qualitystandards to make a product that is the industry leader.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     ManufacturingQuality ControlForeign CompetitionProduct DevelopmentUser Needs.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>